{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476342"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:45:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:45:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13734"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13734"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.79,0.11,0.03,0.04,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6353"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54347"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6353"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39856"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2396"},{"type":"tags","id":"3341"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17099"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54347"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department by his parents one hour after accidentally ingesting several tablets of his mother\u0027s antidepressant medication. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations. On examination, he appears agitated with a temperature of 38.2\u00b0C, pulse rate 140/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, and SpO2 98% on room air. He has dilated pupils and hyperreflexia in both lower limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of the medication that would cause this clinical picture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibition of serotonin reuptake in the synaptic cleft","Increased serotonin release from presynaptic vesicles","Agonism of postsynaptic serotonin receptors","Inhibition of monoamine oxidase in the presynaptic neuron","Increased sensitivity of postsynaptic serotonin receptors"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture described is consistent with serotonin toxicity, which is typically caused by selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs). The primary mechanism of action of SSRIs is to \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibit the reuptake of serotonin by the presynaptic neurons\u003C/strong\u003E, thereby increasing the concentration of serotonin in the synaptic cleft. In overdose, this leads to serotonin toxicity, characterised by altered mental status, autonomic instability, and neuromuscular hyperactivity - as seen in this child.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESSRIs do not \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease the release of serotonin from presynaptic vesicles\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the mechanism of action of drugs like MDMA (ecstasy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESSRIs are not \u003Cstrong\u003Eagonists of postsynaptic serotonin receptors\u003C/strong\u003E. They do not directly stimulate these receptors, but rather increase the available serotonin to bind to them.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonoamine oxidase inhibitors\u003C/strong\u003E are a different class of antidepressants that inhibit the breakdown of serotonin, noradrenaline and dopamine in the presynaptic neuron. SSRIs do not have this effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no evidence that SSRIs \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease the sensitivity of postsynaptic serotonin receptors\u003C/strong\u003E. The effect is primarily due to increased synaptic serotonin levels rather than altered receptor function.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["SSRIs inhibit the reuptake of serotonin by presynaptic neurons, thereby increasing serotonin levels in the synaptic cleft.","Serotonin toxicity is characterised by altered mental status, autonomic instability, and neuromuscular hyperactivity."],"references":["Michael Hirsch, Robert J Birnbaum, Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors: Pharmacology, administration, and side effects. In: UpToDate. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/selective-serotonin-reuptake-inhibitors-pharmacology-administration-and-side-effects","Xuev S, Ickowicz A. Serotonin Syndrome in Children and Adolescents Exposed to Selective Serotonin Reuptake Inhibitors - A Review of Literature. J Can Acad Child Adolesc Psychiatry. 2021 Aug;30(3):156-164. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8315218/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39856"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13734"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39856"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-04T11:25:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-04T11:26:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6353"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54347"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/